{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":19513,"record_hash":"sha256:9005f1320462cd2f322e983cfc0b99607b076e918c4da3721e288f02e7e6f995","timestamp":"2026-05-10T08:42:15.922Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"I do have one better suggestion: use `serde` only for the scalar metadata structs.\n\nSomething like:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Serialize)]\n#[serde(rename_all = \"kebab-case\")]\nstruct SourceMetadata {\n    agent: String,\n    #[serde(skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")]\n    provider: Option<String>,\n    #[serde(skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")]\n    model: Option<String>,\n    #[serde(rename = \"tool-version\", skip_serializing_if = \"Option::is_none\")]\n    tool_version: Option<String>,\n}\n```\n\nThen one small helper writes serialized string fields under a prefix:\n\n```rust\nwrite_metadata_fields(handle, &source_prefix, &source_metadata)?;\n```\n\nThat gives us the thing you’re reaching for:\n\n- field names live on the Rust type\n- persistence names are attached with `serde(rename...)`\n- call sites stop doing key-string plumbing\n- no custom proc macro, no key enum, no builder framework\n\nI would **not** use this for everything. GitMeta sets/lists like `agent-sessions`, `sources`, and `transcript` are operations, not just fields, so those should stay explicit. But for scalar field groups like source metadata and maybe session `schema` / `updated-at`, serde-backed structs are a pretty reasonable idiom.\n\nSo my actual recommendation is: replace the marker-type constants with small persisted metadata structs plus one helper. That’s better than what I just changed.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-10T08:42:15.922Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}